Data Analysis Protocol DOMn4¶

Aims of the current study¶

This project is intended to isolate the various features responsible for the presence of oblique marking in Iranian languages. The initial project focuses on the Hewramî language spoken in Hewreman Text (Mohammadirad), the Northern Kurdish variety of Dihok (Karim), Vafsi (Stilo), and Zazaki (Dogan).

The data¶

This program runs a series of operations with a table as its input like the following:

  • word: the instance of each nominal
  • sentence: the utterance in which the token occurred
  • language: the language of the text (e.g., H Text, NK Duhok, etc.)
  • text: The text where the item occured if relevant to the langauge
  • sentence_number: a running count of sentences
  • word_num: a running count of all words/cltics
  • previous_men: how many times the word was previously mentioned
  • distance: cuurent sentence number minus the sentence number of the previous mention
  • theta_role: csubj, csubjpass, dative, dep, det, dobj, expl, intj, mark, meta, neg, nmod, npadvmod, nsubj, nsubjpass, nummod, oprd, parataxis, pcomp, pobj, poss, preconj, predet, prep, prt, punct, quantmod, relcl, xcomp
    • A: agent
    • S: single intransitive argument
    • P: patient/direct object
    • PPC: adpositional complement
    • R: recipient/goal
  • stem:
    • prs: the present/imperfective stem
    • pst: the past/perfective stem
  • oblique: oblique-marked nominal = 1; not-oblique/direct = 0
  • number:
    • sg: singular
    • pl: plural
  • gender:
    • m: masculine
    • f: feminine
  • attribution:
    • na: no attribution
    • gen: has a genitival possessor
    • att: has an attributive adjective
  • semantic_class_animacy:
    • 1: first-person pronoun
    • 2: second-person pronoun
    • 3 anim: animate third-person pronoun
    • 3 inan: inanimate third-person pronoun
    • VIP: main character ina story
    • kin: familial terms
    • human: human
    • magical: magical beings (d\^ew, per\^i, cin, etc.)
    • personified: personified entities
    • animal: animals
    • plant: plants
    • place: locations (the countryside, Kurdistan, etc.)
    • count: countable objects (books, keys, clothes, etc.)
    • mass: non-countable objects (rices, water, etc.)
    • abstract: concepts (love, derw\^e\c{s}\^i, kurdayet\^i, etc.)
  • quantification: preceded by quantifier = 1; not preceded by quantifier = 0
  • definiteness_marked:
    • def: is there a morpheme that marks of definiteness (-eke, -e)
      • indf: is there a morpheme that marks indefiniteness (-ek, -\^ew, -\^en, etc.)
      • abs: no morpheme that marks these things
  • definiteness_type:
    • na: not definite
    • anaph: anaphoric definiteness: "The referent has an antecedent in the preceding textual context: A man and a woman entered. The man sat down."
    • bridge: bridging definiteness: "The referent has not been previously mentioned in the discourse context, but its existence can be inferred from associated expressions: We bought a new car, but the brakes were faulty. "
    • pn: proper nouns: "The noun is conventionally associated with a specific entity: Sweden, Angela Merkel, Mount Kilimanjaro"
    • poss: possessum: "The noun is accompanied by a grammatical possessor: my house, their child, Henry’s birthday"
    • deict: preceded by a demonstrative determiner
    • unique: unique referents: "Entities which are assumed to be uniquely identifiable by all members of a given speech community, hence require no preceding or inferable mention: the sun, the river (in a given community), the President etc." - situ: situational definiteness: Identifiability is achieved through the immediate speech context, possibly aided through additional gestures and adverbial expressions: the man over there (pointing). (from Nourzaei 2021)
  • enumerated: preceded by a number = 1; else = 0
  • verb_dist: distance from the verb to which it is syntactically

protocol¶

Based on these data, we should be able to find the relationships between any of these features in these and other Iranian langauges. The focus of the current project is to work with the data set restricted to direct objects and to identify which features are indicative of oblique marking. However, for varieties with overt definiteness marking, we could identify what fridicts that as well. Additionally, differential marking of adpositional complements and Agents will likely be a good extension of this project.

# stem to binary
binary_dict = {'pst':1, 'prs':0}
df_Text['stem'] = df_Text['stem'].map(binary_dict)

# number to binary
binary_dict = {'pl':1, 'sg':0}
df_Text['number'] = df_Text['number'].map(binary_dict)

# gender to binary
binary_dict = {'f':1, 'm':0}
df_Text['gender'] = df_Text['gender'].map(binary_dict)

#perform get_dummies on attribution
dummy = pd.get_dummies(df_Text.attribution,prefix='ez', prefix_sep='_', dtype='int64')
df_Text = df_Text.join(dummy)

#perform get_dummies on definiteness_marked
dummy = pd.get_dummies(df_Text.definiteness_marked,prefix='def_m', prefix_sep='_', dtype='int64')
df_Text = df_Text.join(dummy)
df_Text = df_Text.drop(columns=['word', 'attribution', 'semantic_class_animacy', 'quantification', 'definiteness_marked', 'definiteness_type', 'enumerated', 'theta_role', 'sentence', 'language', 'text', 'sentence_number',  'word_num'])

depths = range(1, 21)
acc_depth = []
for i in depths:
    dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 10, max_depth = i)
    dt.fit(train_data, train_labels)

#Create a new list for the accuracy values of a pruned decision tree.  Loop through
#the values of ccp and append the scores to the list
acc_pruned = []
ccp = np.logspace(-3, 0, num=20)
for i in ccp:
    dt_prune = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1, max_depth = best_depth, ccp_alpha=i)
    dt_prune.fit(train_data, train_labels)
    acc_pruned.append(dt_prune.score(test_data, test_labels))

plt.plot(ccp, acc_pruned)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xlabel('ccp_alpha')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.show()
